review.reviewBody:
Like Specialized or not, they did the r&d and testing on how to make the short saddle work. The incredible success of that saddle has led everyone else to imitate, but probably without the r&d and testing. The Bontrager Aeolus works. I do like the concept of the short saddle. The Specialized is a revelation and I put it on all my bikes. The Bontrager is a close second. 

I still try to find something even better. Neither the Shimano (Pro) Stealth nor this Fizik Argo Tempo R3 works for me. The Fizik tries to differentiate from the Specialized Power by being 2 cm longer, as if that might get folks who don't like stubby saddles to like this one. But, that doesn't really change this to a normal saddle. And Fizik made the cutout wider than the Specialized Power cutout (which is already really wide). Too wide. I normally ride a 155 saddle, but the cutout on this (slightly) narrower 150 gouged my thighs because I was sitting "in the hole". I tried different tilts of the saddle and testing it by rocking my hips forward and back to find the sweet spot. Not sweet for me. 

You can buy all but the Bontrager here so something from Competitive Cyclist can probably match your preference. Others have given this one a good review and others have pointed out the gouging from the ridges. See if you can try before you buy.
review.name: Doesn't beat the Specialized Power
comment: Thanks for your review Lewis. I'm sorry the saddle didn't work out in this case. I'm following up you directly.

review.reviewBody: Seventh saddle I've tried and this is a winner. It combines really great sitbone support with a generous cutout so you can sit up or ride in near TT like position with no pressure. Materials are premium and a great, minimalist aesthetic. My only complaint is my Argo didn't find me sooner.
review.name: Answer to my prayers

review.reviewBody: I took a one hour ride with this saddle on my trainer and I was just dying to get it off. Notice that the edges around the cutout of this saddle are hard and not rounded like Selle Italia's. This just failed to conform to my anatomy and created some intense pressure points at my seat bones. Maybe this design just isn't suited for female riders? My hip width is 130 mm, and the cutout was more than large enough. I think the angular shape of this saddle is meant to look cool, but sacrifices comfort to do so.
review.name: Rough edges on inside of cut-out

review.reviewBody: I had tried other saddles and found the one, might take a few rides to break in but this is the most comfortable saddle I've had. No more pain after long rides and feel like I can go on forever.  Great product !!
review.name: Great saddle

review.reviewBody: Replaced a Fizik Aliante with this Fizik Argo Tempo R3 (150mm) and couldn't be happier. It's a racing saddle so you're not getting padding and gel like you would on a Selle SMP Gel Flow, for example (I run that one on a Cinelli Supercorsa and it's fantastic). This Fizik looks great, contours well, weight is solid and is just an excellent saddle for endurance or racing. Have put a few hundred miles on this already on my Bianchi Infinito and it's just a solid product with ample padding and much more comfortable than an Aliante for example.
review.name: Great saddle, try it

review.reviewBody: Similar to the Specialized Power saddle, but I've been digging this better.  It's fantastic!
review.name: Excellent!

review.reviewBody:
This jacket is awesome. I bought this in black (anthracite) a few years ago when it was on sale and it's still in perfect shape. Possibly both my biggest gear splurge and best investment in gear to date. It's so cozy, packable, and has kept me warm during cold nights in the backcountry. For reference, I usually wear a size small in tops, bought this in a small, and it's the perfect fit - comfortably fits a base layer and fleece under it too.

This Memorial Day weekend I really tested its performance though - I climbed Mount Baker and one person in my party forgot their shell. It was snowing, windy, and in the 10s/20s F for most of the 2 days. I would normally never wear a down puffy without a shell in any precip or wind, but knew this jacket was supposed to have some water resistance, so I gave them my Arcteryx hard shell (for reference: also size small in their updated/bigger Beta AR sizing) and wore this puffy as my only/combined insulation and shell layer. I was pretty worried about it soaking through and getting hypothermia as we gained elevation - but this thing kept me totally warm and dry, and I didn't even feel the windchill cut through it. I also got to test out the pocket placement with a harness on for roped glacier travel, since this was my outer layer. Although I don't think the pockets are necessarily designed for a harness / placed higher up, I was able to use the pockets for snacks, extra glove liners, etc. and have no complaints. My helmet fit great under the hood, too - and the hood stayed put shockingly well in the wind.

I don't know if this jacket would hold up as well in rain, and I would never *plan* to wear it again as a shell, but am super thankful that it worked out. Can't recommend this enough - it's worth the investment!
review.name: Can't recommend this jacket enough

review.reviewBody: I am so pleased with this jacket. It's light to wear, but incredibly warm. Even in shirt sleeves and no sweater underneath, I'm warm, and I tend to be cold as a rule. The zipper slips easily, and the material is soft and comfortable. When I sit down, it doesn't pull at the bottom, but if that ever happens, I can unzip from the bottom. The wrists neck down to keep my arms warm, and the back is longer, to keep my behind warm. The side pockets zip to keep belongings safe. The top of the zipper has a small cover to protect my chin. I'm a swimmer, so I have broad shoulders, and coats often pull across the bust when I reach forward. But this jacket doesn't do that. There is enough room across the shoulders and in the arms for my arms to move freely, almost like they knew we might be climbing in it. :-) I would have liked more inside pocket space, and although I understand the hood size is to accommodate helmets, that isn't what I want it for, so it's huge. But these are tiny comments - I love this jacket, so much so, I bought two of them, for the time when the first one gets broken or goes MIA. This is the nicest jacket I've ever owned, and I've worn down jackets all my life.
review.name: The nicest jacket I've ever owned

review.reviewBody: I purchased both this jacket and the Rab Mythic Ultra (each in small) and wanted to offer some comparative observations. I am 5'3" and 130 lbs, a pretty standard small/4/27. I am looking for a lightweight and very warm jacket as an emergency to carry on ski tours and to descend in (I climb in pretty light layers and want something to throw on for a cold decent, and it needs to have room for holding my skins while still looking okay back at home), as well as for everyday work and travel in Wyoming winters. The 2 jackets are comparable in length, but the Neutrino is a bit narrower in the hips, making me wonder how it would do when you need to pull it out and pop it over other layers on a transition. The Neutrino's material feels slightly stiffer as if it would hold up better to snags while skiing through the trees, compared to a thinner/silkier feel to the Mythic Ultra's material. The Neutrino has an interior chest pocket and microfleece-lined main pockets, while Mythic Ultra has an exterior chest pocket and non-lined main pockets. The Neutrino's hood has a velcro piece to shorten if wearing without a helmet, while the Mythic Ultra's hood is hard to get tight enough on the head without a helmet to keep out the wind. The Neutrino did not come with a stuff sack, while the Mythic Ultra does. This all makes sense, as the Mythic Ultra is a true mountaineering jacket while the Neutrino is built for skiing and casual use. Still undecided about which to keep! The Neutrino in the red (heather/grapefruit) color is gorgeous.
review.name: A touch narrow in the hips

review.reviewBody: After a few years, I had to send the product in for repair and they told me that the battery could not be replaced and they would offer me a 15% discount on my next purchase. Not exactly what I would have expected for a quality product
review.name: Jetforce

review.reviewBody:
I bought a jet force pro 3 years ago and only activated the air bag system at the beginning of each season. 

Last winter I tried to charge the pack only to find out the battery no longer takes a charge.

Tried to get a replacement battery 7 months ago from a local dealer with no reply back from black diamond, although I see that the battery is available now…

Ended up buying a second bag at the beginning of the winter that was barely used and it had the same problem…

I’ve heard of the same problem from multiple people. This bag is unreliable and you’re better off with a canister in my opinion.

Ended up trashing both black diamond bags and went with the mammut system.
review.name: Battery doesn’t last

review.reviewBody:
Great pack. Haven't had to use it yet in an emergency situation. But have tested it a couple times. Everything pretty user-friendly and easy to use. I was amazed at how easy it is to re-pack the airbag after it's been deflated after use. Having the ability to test this bag is well worth the price.

I was worried that the diagonal ski straps weren't wide enough for my powder skis; the straps just looked pretty small. But...it fit my 118 underfoot K2's just fine. 

If I had a gripe at all...it would be that it's tough to haul water with this pack. I haven't tried using a reservoir yet...but I'm not really even sure where you would have the reservoir in the pack. If you're rocking a water bottle, it's a little inconvenient having to unzip the whole pack to get to it. Certainly not a deal breaker though. I bought the 35L expansion, and that's what I primarily use. Tons of space...just a little cumbersome digging out a water bottle. 

Overall, I'm very happy this pack!
review.name: Great pack...hopefully I never have to use it.

review.reviewBody: I'm super stoked on this update to the Jetforce. Carries better, fits more stuff, and the zip on/off compartments make it customizable to the day's objective. Love having a battery powered  airbag so I never have to hesitate to pull it. It also pairs with my phone for updates and diagnostic checks which is super convenient!
review.name: Jetforce 2.0!!

review.reviewBody:
I love the round nature of this bag. It rides so comfortable and barely notice the weight it carries so well. My 3 gripes: 
- no hydration hose exit  (can diy one myself)
- the fancy buckles are a little over engineered and don’t buckle when there’s snow in them which is all the time on storm skiing days 
- I can’t figure out the split board carry?? Where are the top straps?  Can anyone help with a photo upload of this??
review.name: Love this pack for comfort but…

review.reviewBody:
I am extremely picky when it comes to backpacks, and I am thoroughly impressed by the 35L Vivid. 
The main things I look for in a pack:
-Ergonomic fit, 
-Well-designed pockets
-utility in variable situations
-Reinforced construction on common wear points

Things I despise in backpacks:
-black hole pack, minimal exterior pockets
-one entryway
-limited use pack

The Vivid fit, shoulder straps, and adjustment points are comfortable and can adjust the pack quite well regardless of the load or clothing you're wearing. Feels comfortable all day.

pockets are a subjective point for everyone, but I like the easy access pockets on the shoulder straps, hip belt, and top of the pack. It keeps things like, headlamps, in-reach, keys, sunglasses, and sunscreen in easy-to-use spots and out of your main compartment. The designated AVY sectional is very well thought out and is extremely quick to access. The pockets divide out your gear well, making it easy to access and keep track of. That's what counts when you're in a snowstorm and need to keep things organized.

The roll-top AND back access are my favorite features on this pack. it can easily pack 35-40 L when fully maxed out. you can also compress it down to (what feels like 25L) and still have a structured pack.

Pingora went out of their way to reinforce the back of the pack with foam, and material around the ski straps. I used my pack at least 100 days this year. there is no sign of wear on any points. I see this pack lasting for years to come.

I don't often write reviews but this is one of my favorite backpacks I've used and it has truly enhanced my backcountry skiing/splitboarding/snowmobile experience.
review.name: Perfection

review.reviewBody: Perfect bag for longer touring days. Well thought design and awesome sustainability story. Plus a local UT brand. Will be buying more in the future

review.reviewBody: I put these to use in a few areas on a summit to San Gorgonio mountain and they were helpful both in icy frozen snow and old packed snow. I haven't used them in any fresh powder yet. The belt system is ok to use with gloves, but isn't perfect. If anything falls off its guide or buckle it can take some extra fiddling to get it back in place, and if you're backpacking in really cold conditions at elevation this is really tiring, so take time to practice in gloves at home, because it'll probably happen once or twice. I can't speak to durability yet, but everything looked fine after using them. Overall not bad, but could improve the strap system. Pretty comfortable, never came off, and worked great up and down slopes.
review.name: Pretty capable wilderness snowshoe

review.reviewBody: I live in northern Canada so a jacket like this is a NEED. I am 6'0 and 190 pounds athletic build. I went with my usual size large and it is reaaaally big make. I wear huge hoodies under it and still so much room. It goes all the way down to the bottom of my calves. It's like wearing a sleeping bag to work everyday and it's amazing for walking my dog in these frigid winter temps.
review.name: Size Down

review.reviewBody: We just moved from Los Angeles to Iowa and I felt I needed something more than your average parka for the adjustment. I love almost everything about this jacket: the look, the fit, how warm it keeps my lower body, etc. I'm 5'7", 145 pounds and a Medium was perfect. It's not fitted and I can easily wear a bulky sweatshirt underneath. The only reason I couldn't give it 5 stars is that there's not much down/insulation around the shoulders. I was outside at a parade and my shoulders were the only parts of me that felt the cold. My legs and body were super warm though. I'd probably still buy it again.
review.name: Love almost everything about this jacket

review.reviewBody: Soft and warm for sure! Love that the bottom zipper zips up so you can walk easier in it. Every bit worth the price tag!

review.reviewBody:
These are a great snow pant shell. They are super comfortable 
and seem to run true to size. I love all the vents which allow for different degrees
of cooling off. The fabric is soft, stretchy, and forgiving as well. They are perfect for 
a nice day boarding/skiing on the slopes or for wearing on 
a winter snowshoe hike. I highly recommend these!
review.name: Comfortable softshell pants

review.reviewBody: Fit was perfect. Lots of pockets and room for storage. Lightweight yet warm for winter walks. Love it!
review.name: Perfect for winter walking

review.reviewBody: Perfect fit, move with you in the right places, and all the pockets/extras I could wish for in my backcounty pant.
review.name: Stretchy perfection

review.reviewBody: These overall seem wonderful and I look forward to getting a ton of use out of them this season. HOWEVER, especially with this style of product where the zippers/gaiter prevent straightforward alteration there really really needs to be a shorter inseam option! Tons of women have shorter inseams but still can't wear a size "small"
review.name: Great product but I wish it came in a short length!!

review.reviewBody: I have large thighs and these did not work for me. Very tight around the thighs!!! I tried the XL but they were too big. I found a pair of bibs from another company that work well instead. OR needs some curvy sized bottoms! Otherwise they seemed like nice pants.
review.name: Had to return

review.reviewBody: I love these shell pants. They are great for ski touring as they dont insulate too much but provide a good amount of water repellency and durability. I still fall quite a bit as im newer to skiing and these keep me nice and dry and I dont worry about them ripping or tearing even if I fall into a bush or scrap against a tree. I love the removable ankle cuffs, and the pockets on these are great. The higher waist at the back is great for when im squatting or sitting to keep my back better protected!
review.name: 10/10 pant - wont buy anything else again.

review.reviewBody: I love these pants so far! I've used them 5 times for backcountry touring and they are cute, very comfortable, reasonably warm but also breathable, and the vents are great. I like the adjustable hip belt for a snug fit. My beacon fits in my front or back thigh pocket.
review.name: Great pair of pants for trail breaking

review.reviewBody: These are the softshells you want. All the best features including integrated inner gaiters. Makes snowshoeing while pulling a toddler on a sled a breeze! Makes raking wet leaves on a freezing cold PNW rainy Saturday less of a chore! Comfortable is an understatement. Let's just say if my employer had a more lax dress code, I would wear these to office (PS...these pants do not create the dreaded "Seinfleld Swooshing" sound commonly associated with weather resistant fabrics). Another 10/10 from a loyal OR customer.
review.name: Upgrade from a 10 year old pair of OR Windstopper Softshells

review.reviewBody: I like all the features on these pants. I ordered according to sizing chart but the pants are way too big in the hips. I knew the lenght would be too long, I'm 5'1", so I'm used to having too long pants but the articulated knee came down below my knee. Unfortunately, I will be returning this item.
review.name: I would buy if the legs were shorter

review.reviewBody: The Trailbreaker II womens pants is great! Good fit, Size M fits with room for underlayers for 130lbs, 5'5". The fold up back waist is excellent, fits against the lower back and keeps out drafts. The robust fabric below the knee area is a good idea, will protect the pant from scrapes in the bush and on skis. I bought the light pewter for a change from black, light pewter colour is nice, looks good with many colours of jackets & shirt , the light pewter , like most grey clothing, stains easily, so far have been able to get all stains out by using a stain remover on the area before washing. The velcro waist adjusters are bulky and cause abrasion damage to the lining of jackets, shirts, tshirts , I removed the velcro & elastic to solve this , pant still fits me perfectly without the adjuster. The many pockets are convenient however the shape of the zip hand pockets goes towards the front of the inner thigh, so when there is an object such as a pocketknife or mini tool in the pocket it slides to the front of the inner thigh and feels uncomfortable. I tried placing pocketknife & mini multitool in the thigh pocket but then they can be felt close to the knee, have been using the little pocket to back of left lower thigh for those items, is OK but not perfect. The zipper pulls for the hand pocket and the thigh vents are the same size and very near each other...it is easy to accidentally use the thigh vents as the pocket resulting in items falling down inside the pant, maybe having a slightly different shape for the zipper pulls would be helpful to prevent this. The bottom of the cuff and the snow cuff barely fits over my winter footwear, insulated rubber boots&mukluks even with the zipper open. The snap & zipper pull at the cuff are both tiny and can't be used with gloves/mitts on. The pant fabric feels great, having stretch and abrasion resistance the pant fabric pulls on easy over an underlayer with a smooth surface but not over fuzzy tights.
review.name: close to perfect pant

name: Trailbreaker II Softshell Pant - Women's

review.reviewBody: I bought my Ride 17s in August, and I'm still running in them. I love the sole and arch support. The height and cushion make me feel like a more confident runner. I got my Ride 17s wet yesterday and decided to wear my Brooks Glycerins today. My entire run I was wishing I was running in my Ride 17s.
review.name: My Favorite Trainers

review.reviewBody: I absolutely LOVE the Saucony Ride 17!!! It is is an amazing daily trainer! The shoe feels light with some firm cushion underfoot, but none of the sinking feeling that I've gotten from other shoes. The Rides also have the “rocker” feel that gives you the sensation of being pushed forward with each step! Almost like a supershoe, but for a daily trainer shoe! Yay! Thank you Saucony! I love these and need them for my runs!
review.name: Favorite daily trainer and workout shoe!

review.reviewBody: I’ve gone through all the brands and this is the shoe with the best construction and support.  I wore Saucony years ago and I’m glad I’ve returned.
review.name: Fit and function

review.reviewBody: So disappointed. The Ride 16 was the perfect shoe. It fit well, hugging the foot without being too tight; it was not heavy or bulky feeling, and it also looked nice. I was afraid to get the Ride 17 based on some negative comments about it, but the Ride 16 had been so great that I had to give the Ride 17 a try. I do not like it. They took a great shoe and really turned it into a dud. I have a relatively high arches, but the Ride 16 hugged my foot and didn't need any extra expensive insole. The Ride 17 is the EXACT OPPOSITE. On the waist of the shoe that runs along the arch, the outer part is now stiffer than it used to be because the word "saucony" has been added along there in a plastic material. That hard material means that when you pull the laces to tie the shoe, it no longer hugs the inside of the foot. It's just boxy, making for a shoe that feels bulky and heavy. It also has zero support inside. I've put insoles from a different pair of older sneakers into the Ride 17 and demoted the Ride 17 from a running shoe to my everyday sneaker. I've been very disappointed in this "updated" model.
review.name: So disappointed in the Ride 17 when compared to th

review.reviewBody: The shoes are very comfortable but they squeak when moving.

I've bought them shoes do to needed a good a great shoe to work in. I work on my feet and do alot of standing and walking. They have been a great shoe for the job. I'm sure I'll be buying another pair later, in another color. :)
review.name: Comfortable

review.reviewBody:
I have been running in Saucony shoes for the last 10+ years and the ride 17 has been the best yet!
I am a 73 year old runner who still can do half marathons and I’ve been injury free for quite a few years now so my shoes and training are working. ( i run about 1500 kms/year) 
The roomy toe box, the pull tab on heel and the extra long laces have fixed all the minor issues that I had with the ride 16. 
The shoe feels light and springy and has a “rocker” feel that pushes you forward… almost pushing you to run faster!❤️
Ps.. I also have the Xodis Ultra which I love! Great fit and traction on the trails!
review.name: Women’s Ride 17

review.reviewBody: I just bought these and Guide 17, and out of the 2 I prefer the Ride 17. Details I noticed is that Ride has a slimmer, snug fit especially in the front. The laces have a bouncy spring. They both have great bouncy support when running and walking, except for my foot at least, Ride's arch and toe support fit best for me. Guide had an arch support that felt too far in the back and created an unnatural bump where it wasn't supposed to be. Guide felt too wide in front the top half to the toe area. The overall base of the Guide was much more pronounced like extra support, I'm not a fan of that look for me. Ride was less over the top I felt.  Overall shape and look of the Ride felt closer to what a running shoe looks like for me, Guide felt like being extra - personal preference.  If ever anyone else wondered between the 2 models like I did, I hope that was helpful. I've returned the Guide, and only worn the Ride out once so far, and it's unlike any runners I've ever worn, it's really cool how it's got a peppy bounce to my step, and can't wait to run in them too. I'm very happy my friend recommended these!
review.name: Unlike any runners I've ever worn

review.reviewBody: My wife found the Ride 17 to wide for her.  We were able to find the Ride 15 elsewhere which fits her best.

review.reviewBody:
The belt seems to be fine. As pictured. Although perhaps a bit thinner than I was expecting. 

What I really wanted to note is that the sizing is somewhat suspect. The size numbers are meant to be centimetres. I ordered the 110 cm size to begin with. However the actual size is 124 cm plus 3 cm for the buckle for 127 cm total length. I then ordered one of the 95 cm size belts and that came in at 108 cm plus 3 cm for the buckle for 111 cm total length. Maybe Swedish centimetres are longer or there is a special convention for specifying belt sizes that I am not aware of but either way the sizing isn't entirely obvious. So be warned that if you are selecting a belt size online you may in fact need a smaller size than you think.
review.name: Questionable Sizing

review.reviewBody:
My new favorite boots! 
I'll admit, I was worried when I first tried them on because they were a little stiff in the ankle, but I wore long socks while breaking them in to avoid them rubbing. They feel great after a few wears and they are so cute, comfortable, and easy to keep clean. They are my go to pair. I stand all day for work.
review.name: Get them!

review.reviewBody:
Women’s 7.5 - Medium Width ordered 
Quality is great. Love the touch and feel of the leather. I bought these for fashion purposes, but they have a pretty hard toe box so I could use them for work as well. 
Color: Cordovan - a great dark chocolate brown. Could wear well with black or brown. 
Size: I am a standard 7.5 in Ariat. I have English lace up riding boots (15+ years old and going strong) and calf high western boots both 7.5 and both are a great fit. Bought these Chelsea’s in a 7.5 and they are a bit big in the toe and heel. However. My arch isn’t being compressed which tends to happen in a lot of flat boots. And I can wear thicker socks to make up the space. I also don’t mind having a bigger toe box. If you are on the more narrow side, order down and your standard size and pick the best fit. I didn’t see another width option aside from medium so that may be the standard here. All in all, I love them and am excited to wear them
review.name: Great quality: Women’s 7.5 - Medium Width

review.reviewBody: Better than expected. First off I have some foot issues. Have a joint replacement in my one foot and therefore suffer from Sesamoiditis. Almost no shoe is comfortable. I read many many reviews and decided to give the black waterproof Chelsea a go. I run between a 9.5 and 10 in shoes ( 10 in Hoka, mostly 9.5 in Vionic ) so I never know what to order on line. I went with the 10 and it was ok in length with some extra room but my heel slipped way too much so I returned for the 9.5. They were still fine in length but a bit more snug in the heel so I wore them around the house to decide if I would keep or return them. To my surprise they were very comfortable and then I purchase the grey suede Chelsea. These have a bit more room and were comfortable right out of the box. I’ve kept both. I will say I placed my dr scholl’s custom fit orthotics in them. I’ve worn them both out for an evening and am so happy to have found them. Love them and highly recommend you give them a try.
review.name: Better than expected

review.reviewBody: They are my favorite shoes. They are so beautiful and comfortable! I love them so much that when my dog ate the first pair I brought a second!
review.name: So good had to buy them twice!

review.reviewBody: They fit but everything was off, weight, balance how they moved and supported my feet. Plus they rubbed my shins. Have a rule if they aren't comfortable back they go.  I will be returning them when order is complete and I see if there are problems with other parts of order.
review.name: Weird Fit & Oddly Uncomfortable

As for waterproofness, I haven’t worn them working in the rain but I have walked through wet grass and my toes were dry. Definitely recommend.

review.reviewBody: I was excited for these studded feet being a Vermonter. The tread seemed fine. However the show itself was so stiff like cardboard and I knew I COULD NOT walk around in these. Even a few steps I could feel the hot spots forming. They were my correct size, so I don't get it. For such a pricey shoe, the material seemed awful. I ended up just buying some strap on treads to add to my current boots.
review.name: Disappointed. Returned

review.reviewBody:
I am a HUGE fan of IceBug footwear, I have purchased several different  models over the years. Started with Ivalo1 which was roomy and soft, and easy in/out with a wide front zipper.  But the Ivalo3 upper bears little resemblance to my old favorite. This boot is far stiffer and less roomy so anyone without a slender foot and ankle, or those with mobility challenges, may find this doesn’t fit even when sizing up. 

If this version of the boot will fit your foot, then it deserves 5 stars! I swear by BUGrip throughout the mountain winters of Utah especially when clearing snow or walking the dog on pavement or frozen trails - anywhere that there is a threat of slipping on ice.

IceBug please bring back a front zipper boot that older less mobile people can use to protect themselves from slipping on icy outdoor surfaces!
review.name: Love BUGrip but fit is so different

The next day, I wore them around Vail and dressed them up with a nice pair of jeans and sweater. They looked great! review.itemreviewed: Long Bear Hooded Down Jacket - Women's
review.reviewBody:
I just received this jacket, and I haven’t had a chance to test it in bitter cold weather yet, but I wanted to review it anyway because I struggled to find reviews and answers to my questions before purchasing. So I’ll provide what info I can, and I hope it helps someone else. 
1. Warmth: Temps usually get to around -15F at least a few times each winter where I live in Iowa, with windchills sometimes down to -20F to -40F. I think this jacket can handle that, at least for short periods. The down insulation is excellent and full, especially on the hood. The outer fabric is very heavy duty and feels waterproof and windproof. I got too hot just trying the coat on in my house and had to take it off because I was overheating after less than 5 minutes on. So far, very promising. It’s much, much warmer than any other jacket I have, which includes some very nice Columbia, North Face, and Eddie Bauer jackets, none of which could handle Iowa winters to my needs. I neither run hot nor cold—I’m pretty average, so YMMV.
2. Pockets: the only pockets you can stick your hands in to keep them warm are all but uninsulated and only lightly lined with a very, very thin fleecy material between your hands and the outer coat shell. There is no way this coat will keep hands warm in serious cold. Also, the height and angle of the pockets is weird, and the fabric digs into my wrists when I hold my hands in them. The pockets are thus good for holding stuff but not for keeping hands toasty or comfortable.
3. Fit: I am 5’5” and 135 lbs, and I bought a medium.The sleeve length is excellent and on the longer side. I have normal to slightly long arms, and the sleeves are a hair long for me, which I love. Hopefully the jacket will work for taller people. The jacket is cut quite slim, and it is very flattering, but it is definitely smaller than your average US size medium jacket. Most of my other jackets are a size small, but I wouldn’t even be able to zip up this coat in a small. If in doubt, size up. The chest, especially, does not have much extra room for larger busts. I am a full B/small C cup, and this coat is as snug as I am comfortable with. It’s almost a hair too tight there, though it fits perfectly everywhere else. Larger busted ladies will probably have some trouble with this jacket. I have no problems with sizing otherwise. The length comes to about 6 inches above my knees, which is long enough to help with the wind and short enough to not restrict mobility.
Color: I bought tapioca, and it looks exactly like the photo. 

Summary: It’s super warm, but the pockets stink. It feels very high quality, and it is flattering, but it runs a little small for US sizing. I am very pleased with my purchase, though I think I would be a little salty if I paid full price. The pockets are really not up to snuff for a $900 jacket. However, I bought this on clearance with an added 20% off coupon to bring the price to around $550, and for that price, I’m very, very happy with it.
review.name: Very warm, pockets stink

name: Long Bear Hooded Down Jacket - Women's

I'm 5'6.5" and the pant length is perfect.  They look slim and neat.  I even wore them to church on a cold day.

Also, it doesn’t feel like I’m wearing huge snow pants or anything. They have a trim look which I love. Based on other reviews and the description, I ordered a size up (size small) so they wouldn’t be too snug. Though, I absolutely could have gotten the XS, as the Small has plenty of room for a layer of leggings to fit underneath, but without being too big on their own.  I’m 5’6” and 115 lbs. I am very happy with my purchase, but will probably order an XS as well for a more slim, pant fit.

review.reviewBody: I'm with Ben.

review.reviewBody:
I purchased these for some 700 30 tires.    The quality of the rubber is fine.   They have maybe 100 miles on them since purchasing.    
The Box size label is 27" by 1 1/4"  with 700 28-32 being the secondary label.   If you are not familiar, a 27" rim has a larger diameter than a 700c rim.    The tubes were difficult to fit on a 700c rim as their diameter, prior to inflation was greater than the rims diameter and I had to fold the tubes over to get them to fit.    Beyond the greater challenges of installing them, I am concerned they will be more prone to flats.
review.name: Presta  700 28-32 are sized for 27" rims

review.reviewBody: I bought these for my gravel bike. I had both tubes puncture within one hour. They could not handle moderate gravel.  I have 25 years of racing and riding experience.  These are the worst tubes I have ever used.
review.name: Do not purchase for gravel.

review.reviewBody: I have been fixing flats on my bike for 15 years and these are the worst inner tubes I?ve encountered. They are very thin, prone to flats, and I even had one explode when I was pumping it up to find a leak (trust me, it was far from being overinflated.)

review.reviewBody: I’ve had mine for over 10 years, it used to be bright yellow. As it more gray/brown than yellow and the zipper finally fave up, I’m buying another one in a darker color
review.name: Over 10 years

review.reviewBody: I have owned this bag for 8 years at this point and it is still going strong. The construction has been incredible - the only real sign of wear is the slightest fraying of the zipper pull - but otherwise, the bag still looks amazing. As others have commented on, I love the versatility and flexibility of this bag and being able to use it as a tote (for more professional settings) or a backpack (for more casual settings). I use the handles on top when I need to maneuver the bag quickly in a particular way, so while it's not a default way of carrying it for me, I still love the functionality of it. I cannot recommend it highly enough!
review.name: Versatile, functional bag going strong 8 years in!

review.reviewBody: I love my Totepack! It is so handy to be able to switch between a backpack and shoulder bag when I am traveling around. It fits a lot, and I've been able to use it on several 1  and 2-night trips. The materials are of superb quality and the leather accents are very attractive.
review.name: Great bag

review.reviewBody: Have had mine for more than a year (in Navy) and still appreciate it as much as when I first purchased.  I use it daily and it has held up like new - excellent quality. Have recommended to friends & get lots of compliments.  I make use of all the features - originally purchased because I liked the combo of bag size/short handles, but use the tote style handles and also convert to backpack straps all the time.
review.name: 100% would recommend

review.reviewBody: I got this back five years ago and use it almost daily to carry my laptop to work. I really like the high water resistance as biking in rain is often the case, also the bike looks great and it’s very practical.. The shoulder straps are too narrow to carry something more heavy. Unfortunately, the color (black in my case) bleached a lot during the time so the bag looks quite worn out … I wonder if other colors can stay as new longer …
review.name: Nice and practical for work

review.reviewBody:
I got the Patina Green color, and I'm loving this bag!
It has a laptop sleeve that I can fit two laptops into, it has a small zipper pouch on the top inside of the bag, and a medium zipper pouch in the front where I keep my wallet and stuff. I use the cross body strap but the handle and backpack straps are really convenient when you need to carry something small with the handle or large with the backpack straps. The bag also looks really nice from the front and you can't tell there are straps on the back unless you turn it around. Really happy with this bag :)
review.name: Perfect medium size!

review.reviewBody: I love this bag in blue. Used it as work and travel bag for years. Very sturdy and the backpack option works great. Fits a small laptop and few books. Needed a bigger one so got the Totepack No. 2.
review.name: Must have bag

review.reviewBody: I have had this bag for 2 years now. I love the look, the versatility, and the space it offers. What I do not love, however, is how the bag bunches up when used as a tote if it is not filled enough; the strap closest to the body pulls and bunches. I have also experienced this when it is used as a backpack. I’ve thought about adding snaps to the back to hold the straps to the bag to accommodate the lack of heft, but am nervous about ruining this gorgeous bag. I’m currently looking for a new bag by Fjallraven, likely a backpack, to use for work. I know it sounds silly, but that was a hard decision for me because I absolutely love the look of this bag. But the adjustable straps of a backpack, may remedy the issue I am having.
review.name: Wish it had structure

review.reviewBody: This is the Mary Poppins bag dream come true! Perfect slim design yet holds all your essentials plus your kids stuff plus those extras that make life on the go easier and more fun. Shoulder bag to backpack means you can go hands free when you need to or have easy access to your stuff. Durable, pretty, functional, Perfect.
review.name: Perfect mom bag

review.reviewBody: I got this bag and was impressed with the quality and colour as soon as I opened it.  That being said, it's unusable to me as a bigger person.  I'm a XXL in women's clothing and the bags straps are too short.  I can get the bag on my back awkwardly but with anything in the bag it becomes uncomfortable. I'm not even that big in the whole scheme of things and generally shop at straight sizes places. I think I will be returning this bag.  It would be nice if strap length was listed.  I just looked at the listing for this bag and it's not there so I'm not sure if I will take the risk and exchange in the hopes something else fits or just return it.
review.name: Not for plus sized people

review.reviewBody:
The overall quality seemed good when they arrived.  The battery placement however makes getting them on difficult if your winter coat has sleeve liners that can get in the way.  I was unable to use them for spinning in my lines so I had to frequently take them off and use my bare hands.  Then of course I had difficulty getting them back on in the wind and cold.  They were very warm but I would not recommend if you need to do anything with your fingers

When they arrived, I noticed a loose thread but thought it may have just been incidental.  After wearing only twice for maybe 20 minutes total the seams separated and they were no longer waterproof.  I so wanted to love these but they were more hassle than a blessing particularly with full charge times exceeding 6 hours!  I had a generator and these spent far more time charging than keeping me warm.

review.reviewBody: These boots were comfortable right out of the box. They’re the most comfortable shoes I have- hands down. I look forward to putting on many miles in these delightful shoes!
review.name: Fantastic hiking shoes

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] Very comfortable boots but definitely not waterproof. Still, cushioned and grippy and probably ok in a light rain. Didn't hold up at all for walking through puddles, though.
review.name: Very comfortable but not waterproof

review.reviewBody:
[This review was collected as part of a promotion.] Finally, a womans boot that is not too narrow!
Super comfy and supportive.
review.name: Perfect!

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] All of the other Keen hiking boots I bought were too heavy and hurt my feet. The Zionic is much lighter and doesn't hurt my feet.
review.name: it's lightweight

review.reviewBody: I purchased this pair of hiking boots to participate in a 20 mile hike. I also brought a pair of tennis shoes with me in the hike in case the boots became uncomfortable on the hike. Well, I did not need the tennis shoes! My new pair of hiking boots were very comfortable and supportive to my feet and ankles throughout the hike. Thank you KEEN for high quality, comfortable products!
review.name: Absolutely Amazing!

review.reviewBody: Keen’s are my go to hiking boot. I wish I would have worn these around the house for a day. The toe box is too narrow. After a few miles I had to suspend my hike and head back to the car, my toes were so sore. I guess I was counting on Keen’s wide toe box. Very disappointed.
review.name: Narrow toe box

review.reviewBody: These are lighter than other boots I've tried on. I liked the color
review.name: Lighter than most hiking boots

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] I recieved the Keen Footwear  Zionic Mid WP hiking boots size 10 color Steel Grey/Magnet from Influencer for my honest review.  The Keen Footware Zionic Mid WP hiking boots in size 10 in Steel Grey/Magnet color were actually a great surprise.  They fit and wear like a hightop tennis shoe.  And, unlike a old fashion hiking boot didn't take a month to break in. It took a week of wearing them daily for an hour or so.  They have a pillow like insole that doesn't seem to be breaking down at all. The insole feels the same as it did on day 1, I have been wearing these daily for at least an hour for the last month. The traction is amazing,  I've been using them while removing really tough weeds and roots in my garden.  The last week I've been wearing them for at least 5 hours daily as I have been gardening  and have had no issues and haven't had any blisters.  I do recommend wearing socks with these boots. These boots also have plenty of toe room.
review.name: The most surprising hiking boot

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] Bought these based on the reviews. The reviews were accurate stating right out the box comfort, couldn't agree more. Comfort, support, grip. Have worn them several times and it's been great each and every time.
review.name: Love Them

review.reviewBody: This is my third pair of Keen hiking boots and the first pair of this type. They are super comfortable and really light weight! I have not worn them that much yet so I can't attest to long term wearing or use but so far they feel and look great.
review.name: So far I love them!

review.reviewBody: New into backpacking, I had a not so great sleeping bag which wasn’t warm at all when it was 40F outside and super windy, I didn’t want to be cold again. I did a lot of research and narrowed it down to this bag and I’m so glad I invested in such a quality product! I stayed so warm in 28F with minimal layers on like a warm cozy cocoon. Love that this is made in America by one single person! Don’t hesitate to invest in this sleeping bag you won’t regret it! I wish they had this in a dog version so I can match with my pup.
review.name: Big upgrade!

review.reviewBody: It feels kind of pointless to write another 5 star review of this bag. But it lives up to the hype. Very warm, well made, light, packable, very puffy, comfy and made in the good ol' USA.
review.name: Lives up to the hype

review.reviewBody:
I never thought i would get used to a mummy bag but I did, especially when it got cold. 20 degrees out and I was roasty toasty in my ultra light western mountaineering sleeping bag. Seriously, when everyone got up and crawled out of their tents someone said he was freezing all night long, another agreed then looked at me and the other guy.
I said I was warm as could be and the other said he was ok but put another shirt on. Then he said I must have had a load a clothes on too. I said nope, just my shorts thats it. It really did hit 20 degrees around 5:30 am and I was absolutely comfortable tucked into my bag. 
I was wonderfully warm. Hearing how the others were not so warm and miserable I felt really good about doing cold weather hiking with my choice of sleeping bags. It,s warm, very lite weight and stuffs down darn near to about a football size.
review.name: I'm big, 6 ft 225 broad shoulder

review.reviewBody: Best sleeping bag so far! Perfect for 3 seasons and super lightweight. Does not come with compression bag, but that is an easy fix! 11l compression bag fits perfect!
review.name: Best so far!

review.reviewBody: This bag is the perfect mix of warm and lightweight for 3-4 season sleeping. There is simply nothing bad about this bag. WM is the best.
review.name: No comparison

review.reviewBody: No break-in period required for me - these were comfortable out of the box.  It's taken me half a life to realize my feet are on the wider side - so I now look carefully at descriptions and reviews.  This toe box is comfortable and accommodating with a medium-thickness hiking sock and the boot provides plenty of cushion and protection while feeling nimble and light.  My first foray into Salewa and I'm very pleased.

review.itemreviewed: Mountain Trainer Lite Mid GTX Hiking Boot - Men's
review.reviewBody:
I’ve had two pair of these, first pair I exchanged broke the lace eye off kicking a stump on accident. The eye material is aluminum or recycled hot wheels car material, it’s not mailable once bent, it’s brittle. 
These are very comfortably lightweight boots, after approximately 120-150 miles of wear (two full weeks archery hunting) the waterproof is completely compromised. My low top keens are more waterproof. These are also not warm whatsoever. They do seem to breathe very well.i still wear these but not when it’s wet at all.
review.name: Comfortable yes, durable no
